Important Reminder today, July 9th:

The Elementary School and Junior/Senior High offices will be open July 8th & 9th, from 9am-3pm for NEW family registration. Prep, Freeze, and Cook!
Message from the desk of Principal Andrews:

We all need to eat while we “shelter in place”. Support Heyworth Organization of Parents and Educators (H.O.P.E.) and 20% of proceeds will go back to H.O.P.E. On April 16th, call 309.444.2948 between 10am-3pm to “shop” the freezer or purchase gift certificates to use at a later date. Prep Freeze Cook staff will let you know what food is available to purchase. You then place your order and it will be delivered to your address on Friday or Saturday.

Help spread the word! 📣

Have a great day!
Mr. Andrews

post_text: Hornet Pride Moments from last Fri. with Ms. Hanrahan & Heyworth Leap
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
Creative Minds

Heyworth Leap
March 13 at 4:02 PM ·

For several weeks, 3rd and 4th grade PALS students have been working on a sustainability project. They chose common items that could be found around the school and are usually thrown away. They then worked in groups to brainstorm how they could upcycle those items into something new and useful. Students also created characters out of recyclable materials and wrote a quick story to put it all together. The final step was recording the story and characters for a fun, interactive presentation. Students worked VERY hard on this short production, and hope you enjoy the final result!

Mr. Lyndon Jason

Heyworth families in the free and reduced lunch program: Our local food pantry will have food available for distribution on Tuesday, March 17th. A grocery bag may be picked up by these families at the church. Someone will be at the United Church, 302 E. Main between the hours of 10:30 -11:30 AM and 5:00 - 6:00 PM on March 17th. They also have volunteers who could deliver a bag if needed. Delivery can be arranged by calling (309) 473-2247.

Have a good day everyone!

post_text:
Hornet Pride Moment🎉

Ms. Quinton’s 1st grade class had fun wrapping up their animal adaptations unit! Each student researched a different animal, identified at least one adaptation, and explained how the adaptation helps their animal survive.
They typed up their adaptation reports in Google Drive. They learned how to highlight sentences and then changed the font, color, and size within their document. They also learned how to search images within kiddle.co and then copy and pasted their image into their document. Thank you Ms. Harris for helping co-teach these Tech lessons!
The Kiddos did amazing with their first digital report! 🤩

post_text:
Important note from the desk of Principal Matt Andrews📣

Our annual “Pennies for the Pantry” drive starts November 7!
Did you know that last year, Heyworth Elementary provided pies to 90 Heyworth residents and donated $500 to the Heyworth Food Pantry to help offset their holiday food basket costs? We were also able to donate $700 to the local Angel Tree Committee to offset their costs in providing a Christmas for kids in Heyworth who would otherwise not have one.

This school-wide service project is a lesson in giving back and Heyworth Elementary students are the best at giving back! As the holiday season approaches, let’s think about those in our community who are less fortunate and give back!

Please bring in loose change, or dollar bills starting November 7th - November 15. The classroom that raises the most money will win an ice cream sundae party! We will be making announcements throughout the week, letting you know the classroom standings.

Let the season of giving fill the halls of Heyworth Elementary School and good luck to all classrooms!
